":"CEM008","plot_notes":"Christian Lane Cemetery, Kensington, Connecticut"},"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[{"type":"military","related_id":"T00459","display_label":"Served in his Troop of horses, Fort William Henry alarm 1757.","link_text":"Col. Elizur Talcott"},{"type":"military","related_id":"H00410","display_label":"Nephew killed June 1757; uncle enlisted that August.","link_text":"Martin Hooker"},{"type":"military","related_id":"H00583","display_label":"Fellow Hooker descendant in same 1757 Fort William Henry alarm.","link_text":"Samuel Hart"},{"type":"cousin_marriage","related_id":"H00420","display_label":"Sister Elizabeth's son who married his daughter Sarah 1807.","link_text":"Hooker Gilbert"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"I00150","display_label":"His son Hooker Gilbert married my daughter Sarah in 1807.","link_text":"Moses Gilbert"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Samuel Hooker","first_name":"Samuel","last_name":"Hooker","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[{"war":"French and Indian Wars","war_id":"WAR003","rank":"Private","rank_start":"Private","rank_end":"Private","rank_year_start":1757,"rank_year_end":1757,"unit":"Maj. Elizur Talcott of Glastonbury — Troop of horses","service_years":"August 1757 — 14 days","battles":["BTL048"],"notes":"At age 31 enlisted in Maj. Elizur Talcott of Glastonbury's Troop of horses for service in the alarm for the relief of Fort William Henry and parts adjacent, August 1757 — 14 days of service. Enlisted approximately two months after his nephew Martin Hooker (H00410) was killed June 10, 1757 in the same war. The connection to Maj. Elizur Talcott (T00459, gen 3 from John Talcott) is a Hooker↔Talcott cross-tree military link."},{"war":"American Revolutionary War","war_id":"WAR004","rank":"Private","rank_year_start":1777,"rank_year_end":1778,"unit":"Capt. Nathaniel Chapman's Company, Lt-Col Joseph Baldwin's Regiment, Col. Mead's drafted men","service_years":"December 28, 1777 – March 1, 1778","notes":"Served under Capt. Nathaniel Chapman in Lt-Col Joseph Baldwin's Regiment at Fishkill, NY. DAR Ancestor #A057686 (Connecticut, Private). Source: Record of Service of Connecticut Men in the War of the Revolution (1889), p. 522."}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"military","header":"Veteran of two colonial wars","body":"Samuel served as Private in two of the colonial era's military campaigns twenty years apart. In August 1757 at age 31 he joined Maj. Elizur Talcott's Troop of horses for fourteen days during the Fort William Henry alarm. Twenty years later at age 51 he served again from December 1777 to March 1778 in Capt. Nathaniel Chapman's Company at Fishkill NY — earning DAR ancestor recognition #A057686."},{"number":2,"category":"military","header":"Enlisted weeks after his nephew Martin's death","body":"Samuel's nephew Martin Hooker — son of Samuel's brother Andrew — was killed in the same war on June 10, 1757 at the deadly sentry post documented in Edward Hooker's 1909 genealogy. About two months later in August 1757, Samuel Hooker Jr enlisted at age 31 in Maj. Elizur Talcott's Troop of horses for the Fort William Henry alarm. Whether the enlistment was motivated by news of Martin's death is undocumented but the timing is suggestive."}],"slug":"samuel-hooker-1726"},"H00229":{"id":"H00229","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":5,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1728,"month":8,"day":27,"city":"Kensington","state":"Connecticut"},"parents":{"father_id":"H00086","mother_id":"I00119"},"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","pa